close_symbols: All OS return-code macros used by OS_ObjectIdGetById (error codes)
explanation:
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: The if condition directly depends on this function's return value. To decide whether the inner branch (call to OS_CondVarBroadcast_Impl) can ever be taken (i.e. whether that code is reachable), the analyzer must know the implementation/semantics and all possible return values/conditions of OS_ObjectIdGetById.
- OS_CondVarBroadcast_Impl: The body of the conditional calls this function. Even if reachability is determined by OS_ObjectIdGetById, the signature/semantics of this callee are needed for a complete analysis of the reachable code (e.g. side-effects, return propagation).
- OS_SUCCESS: The conditional compares return_code to this symbolic value. Its definition (value/name) is required to interpret the condition and to reason about which return codes from OS_ObjectIdGetById satisfy it.
- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE and OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_CONDVAR: These arguments are passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById and can affect its internal control flow and return values. Their definitions/meanings are required to determine if any inputs could lead to OS_SUCCESS.
- OS_object_token_t: Type of the token local variable and out-parameter to OS_ObjectIdGetById. Its layout/semantics may influence OS_ObjectIdGetById behavior (e.g. conversion/validation) and thus reachability.
- osal_id_t: Type of var_id; legal ranges or encoding of IDs can determine whether OS_ObjectIdGetById can succeed for given inputs.
- int32: Return type used in the function; include to fully understand return propagation and standard return-code semantics.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: These are the internal callees used by OS_ObjectIdGetById (per the call graph). To reason about all possible return paths and whether OS_ObjectIdGetById can return OS_SUCCESS, the analyzer may need their prototypes/implementations and the return codes they produce.
- All OS return-code macros used by OS_ObjectIdGetById (error codes): Besides OS_SUCCESS, the set of possible error codes that OS_ObjectIdGetById can return is required to determine whether the conditional branch is conditional (reachable) or impossible (unreachable).

Including the above symbols (prototypes/implementations, macros, and types) gives the next analyst the necessary context to determine whether the conditional and its body in OS_CondVarBroadcast can ever be executed, which is required to assess any violation of the MISRA rule banning unreachable code.
